<br>
I just read another thread with questions about hotkeys. I noticed that not everyone is aware of how powerfull hotkey's are. I have a few I use here and then and they made my life much easier. I'm sure some others have them as well, so what great hotkeys did you invent which saves you time or do a neat little trick? Let's gather the ideas here and I think everyone could learn a few nice things. I'll start with some (no I did not invent all of them, some are &quot;stolen&quot; from other posts)  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The pulling hotkey</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This is an easy one and I'm pretty sure most of the pullers have them. it mostly looks like<br>
<br>
/g Incoming %T<br>
<br>
The trick here is the %T, which is replaced by the name of the NPC/MoB you will bring back. I love that extra information to maybe mem a quick spell or prepare for another strategy. Of course the text can be altered to make the incoming message more funnier. However, some ppl don't like that and want to stick to the plain Inc. Up to the puller :-)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The spell effect hotkey</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Some spells can aid if casted at the correct time, but be dangerous if casted at the wrong time. For example: fearing a snared mob makes it easy, but fearing a non snared mob might be tricky since the feared creature runs away at full pace and might pull the melee's into trouble. So to cast fear one should wait till the mob is snared. To ease the communication you can use a hotkey when the effect has hit. For example:<br>
<br>
/g ##### %T snared #####<br>
<br>
I use the &quot;#####&quot; before and after the msg to get the attention in the fight spam. I don't take chances there :-)) Of course I can only use the key when I see that the spell has landed. Otherwise the fear caster might launch his spell too early. Other spells where this is especially usefull is mez's from Enchanters. It should tell the rest of the group what Mob NOT to attack :-))<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The assist hotkey</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
/assist is a very usefull command. It assures everyone is fighting the same creature and not breaking the mez of the Enchies. Normally one melee (most of the times a warrior) is the designated main tank (or MA for Main Assist) and everyone should use him as a reference. Now to not always have to target him and use /assist you can make a hotkey for it. A lot of people use<br>
<br>
/assist %T<br>
<br>
to assist the current target. However, often it is tricky to target the MA, especially in big raids where the MA is in another group. I therefore tend more to<br>
<br>
/assist name <br>
<br>
e.g. if Balkin is the MA you use<br>
<br>
/assist Balkin<br>
<br>
This will switch your target to whoever target Balkin has at the moment. Quite usefull for all involved in a bigger fight.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The healing hotkey</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Clerics often use that method. The reason is to avoid double heals and to calm the warriors. A spell like &quot;Complete Healing&quot; needs 10 seconds to be casted. If the backup healer jumps in too early there and casts Superior Healing or similar, the group has waisted mana. So what they do is something like<br>
<br>
/g Incoming Complete Healing for %T<br>
/cast 1<br>
<br>
The first is the message showing what the target is, the second line will cast the spell in slot number 1 (top spell slot). Of course the number and text can be adopted to your setting. In addition you could add &quot;/sit off&quot; to make sure you are standing and &quot;/book 1&quot; or &quot;/sit on&quot; to sit down to meditate again. One click to stand up, inform the rest of the party, cast the heal and sit down again... quite neat isn't it?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The &quot;Oh my god I'm going to die&quot; hotkey</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
We all know the situation, you pull too much or get jumped while low on health/mana. The MoB kills us and we have no clue where the corpse is. This hotkey will save us from a lot of troubles:<br>
<br>
/loc<br>
/y<br>
/say Help me, I'm getting attacked by %T<br>
<br>
First line will show you the location of where you got attacked. This will help in finding the corpse again. Second line will cause you to yell for help, so others will see a line like &quot;Ellegon is yelling for help behind you&quot; and 3rd will inform the ones around you what is attacking you and killing you. A level 5 might not want to come to aid if a ghoul is attacking you and rather run for safety him/herself :-)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The spell training hotkey</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Casters should try to keep up the casting abilities at the max of their levels. Some abilities are less used than others unless in specific situations, so they quickly fall behind. To avoid that a lot of casters &quot;train&quot; the abilities by casting the same cheap spell over and over and over again. For example, minor healing (cheapest heal spell). Now to ease on the amount of clicking you can set up the following hotkey. Let's assume the spell to be used is mem'd in the bottom slot (slot  :<br>
<br>
/pause 80,/cast 8<br>
/pause 80,/cast 8<br>
/pause 80,/cast 8<br>
/pause 80,/cast 8<br>
/cast 8 (or /g Finished)<br>
<br>
The trick here is that the pause command is issued AFTER the 2nd command. The pause pauses for x * 10th second. That means /pause 10 would pause for 1 second. Based on the spell you will have to fiddle around a bit with the numbers as it will need time to cast the spell and then to gain control again. The only drawback is that in the case of a fizzle, you will still wait the normal time untill you can cast it again. The last line is either a /cast (being the 5th cast) or a msg to your group that the macro is finished. Since most of the times you will not be grouped while practising you will receive a msg like &quot;You are not in a group&quot;, but the only purpose is to be aware that you can click on the button again :-)) Practicing spells is a lot easier with that setup...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The TRAIN hotkey</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Causing trains can happen. Every player caused one some day in his EQ life. It's part of the risk in certain zones. However, warning others is the least thing you can do. In the hectic of fleeing it's hard to type, so suggest the following hotkey:<br>
<br>
/shout ##### TRAIN TO xxx ZONE #####<br>
/ooc ##### TRAIN TO xxx ZONE #####<br>
/auct ##### TRAIN TO xxx ZONE #####<br>
/say if you can read this, the train is CLOSE !!!!!<br>
<br>
I'm against spam as everyone else, but there is such a thing as too less warning :-) The above hotkey will make sure you cover more than one channel (in case one is turned off) and also tell meditating casters if you are near :-) the xxx is replaced with the zone name to be specific.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The &quot;my spell book is organized hotkey&quot;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The more in levels you raise, the fuller your spell book gets. Now every caster might have his own way of organizing spells. Mine works as follows (and is important for the hotkey to be efficient): On page 1/2 I have the &quot;Most Wanted&quot; spells. It's the spells I use a lot but don't have them mem'd all the time. Currently it holds spells such as Spirit of Wolf, Skin like Nature, Chloroplast, Greater Healing, Cure Disease, Cure Poison and so on. The next pages contain spells I use and switch around from time to time like root, Shield of Spikes, DoT's, DD's and so on. then I have a double page dedicated to all Resists (Poison, Fire, Disease etc.). Following is a double page for my single TP spells, then the Group TP spells, EVAC spells, Animal based and so on. As you can see I organized them by &quot;theme&quot; :-) Now I know my Single TP spells start on page 9, my group tp on page 11, Resists are on page 7, animal on 15 and so on. What I did is several hotkeys with different names:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> M.W (for Most wanted)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
/book 1<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SelfTP</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
/book 9<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> GrpTP</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
/book 11 <br>
<br>
and so on. By clicking on that hotkey I will open the book at the appropriate page automatically. No more flipping back and forth to find the correct spell :-)<br>
<br>
Ok, what else do you have???<br>
