<br>
my &quot;book&quot; hotkey:<br>
<br>
/doability 1  <br>
/doability 2  <br>
/book<br>
/em sits down, opens his book, and begins to meditate<br>
<br>
ability 1 =forage - if you get some food, you can put it away while you watch the blue line grow.  In emergencies, don't worry, you can swap spells with food in your hand<br>
ability 2 = sense heading - you can also work on sense heading while medding, did you know that?<br>
I make the last one long so the group knows I am a) regaining mana b) not able to see.<br>
<br>
I also have an /assist hotkey.  I use the function keys to select the person in the party, not reprogramming the hotkey.  I can also select a monster and use /assist to quickly target who he is hitting so I can damage shield or heal them.  /assist  is exactly the same as /assist %T<br>
<br>
On the Train! hotkey, I suggest one really long message with some caps, not multiple lines.  Folks in the zone appreciate a warning that stands out, but they won't appreciate being spammed, possibly scrolling other important messages out of their text box.<br>
<br>
mine is something like:<br>
<br>
/shout  TRAIN!  %T and %P buddies are after me! LOOKOUT!<br>
<br>
I once hunted with a ranger that had separate hotkeys depending on the con of the creature he was pulling.  Very nice.  Something like:<br>
/g Ho hum, another green %T<br>
/g Blue %T coming in<br>
/g Looks like an even fight with a %T<br>
/g Prepare for battle, a yellow %T incoming<br>
/g Stand up and unsheath your swords, an angry red %T is after me!<br>
<br>
I think he had actually made the more dangerous cons longer and longer lines (my example isn't like that), and kept all the %T near the end, so you could tell in a glance what and how dangerous the pull was.  I think he even had a multi-pull message, and a message (I never saw it, he was good!) if he got an overpull and was headed away from the group.<br>
<br>
I think the optimal sense heading training key is five lines of the following<br>
/pause 20, /doability 6<br>
<br>
I named mine Msens - it can block other hotkeys if it is still running (takes 10 seconds), so you don't want to do it when it isn't &quot;safe&quot; - for example use it on a boat, traveling, medding when no one is pulling.  I don't recommend this for kick or bash, for that reason - you can't stop the hotkey and get on to another hotkey when you need to.<br>
